<ArticleLayout
  title="The Real AI Wealth Transfer Won't Happen at OpenAI"
  description="Why the biggest AI opportunity is not in frontier labs, but in helping ordinary businesses customize intelligence around their real-world workflows."
  date="2026-04-20"
  dateFormatted="April 20, 2026"
  topoSvg={topoSvg}
>
  <h2>TL;DR — 3-Minute Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>The biggest AI opportunity is not building the next frontier model.</strong> It is helping ordinary businesses apply intelligence to their real workflows.</li>
    <li><strong>Mark Cuban's point is simple:</strong> there are roughly 33 million traditional US businesses, and most of them do not need more AI hype. They need practical implementation.</li>
    <li><strong>Generic SaaS is going to get squeezed.</strong> The future is software that adapts to the business, not the business adapting to the software.</li>
    <li><strong>The winner is the integrator.</strong> The person who understands models <em>and</em> understands how a shoe store, a trucking company, or a service business actually runs.</li>
    <li><strong>The real money is in operations.</strong> If you can connect AI to revenue, scheduling, lead handling, follow-up, and execution, you are sitting in the right part of the market.</li>
  </ul>

  <p><strong>By Maxwell Hinman</strong></p>

  <h2>Intro: This Is the Most Important AI Argument Nobody Is Taking Seriously Enough</h2>

  <p>I watched a post on X from <a href="https://x.com/r0ck3t23/status/2046282654161727722?s=46&amp;t=SBgKNyKarCkLy1X3ZaWyEw" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">@r0ck3t23</a> breaking down Mark Cuban's comments on AI, and I think it gets at something a lot of people in tech still do not fully understand.</p>

  <p>The biggest wealth transfer in AI probably is <em>not</em> going to happen inside the companies building the most advanced foundation models.</p>

  <p>It is going to happen in the long tail of ordinary businesses that still run the economy. Shoe stores. Small trucking companies. Contractors. Distributors. Field service businesses. Local operators with real customers, real payroll, and a thousand tiny inefficiencies that nobody glamorous wants to touch.</p>

  <p>That is the market most people keep missing.</p>

  <p>Everyone wants to be close to OpenAI, Anthropic, Google DeepMind, or the next frontier lab. That makes sense intellectually because the models are exciting. But the business opportunity is somewhere else. The opportunity is in taking those models and turning them into something a normal business can actually use without hiring an AI engineer, restructuring the whole company, or blowing six figures on experimentation.</p>

  <p><mark>That is where the practical AI economy gets built.</mark></p>

  <h2>The Real Market Is 33 Million Businesses, Not a Handful of Labs</h2>

  <p>The X post highlighted Cuban's core point: if you are thinking about AI purely as a race to build better models, you are staring at the wrong part of the map.</p>

  <p>There are around 33 million traditional businesses in the United States. Most of them are not trying to train LLMs. They are trying to answer the phone faster, qualify leads, book jobs, reduce admin, stop dropping customer handoffs, and make their software stop fighting them.</p>

  <p>That is the part people in AI circles often underestimate. Most business owners are not sitting around wondering whether GPT-5 is better than Claude or whether open weights will overtake the closed labs. They are wondering why their office manager is drowning, why their CRM is half-updated, why callbacks take too long, and why software they pay for still creates more work than it removes.</p>

  <p><mark>They do not want AI as a science project. They want a machine that takes friction out of the business.</mark></p>

  <p>This is why I think Cuban is probably right. The largest AI wealth transfer is going to show up when intelligence gets customized around the messy operational reality of traditional businesses. Not at the level of abstract model capability, but at the level of actual daily work.</p>

  <h2>The End of Generic SaaS</h2>

  <p>One of the strongest ideas in the video was the prediction that generic SaaS starts to lose its grip. I think that is exactly right.</p>

  <p>For the last twenty years, software has mostly worked like this: a company buys a tool, then bends its workflow to fit the software. That is why so many businesses feel trapped inside clunky CRMs, awkward scheduling tools, weird internal workarounds, and disconnected systems that all technically function but never really fit.</p>

  <p>AI changes that equation.</p>

  <p>If intelligence becomes cheap and flexible enough, software no longer has to be rigid. The software can start adapting itself around the business instead of the business adapting around the software. That is a massive shift.</p>

  <p>And it does not mean SaaS disappears overnight. It means generic software becomes less defensible unless it becomes more customizable, more intelligent, and more embedded in real workflows.</p>

  <p>That is why I think the next wave is going to create demand for a different kind of operator. Not just developers. Not just prompt engineers. Not just consultants in the old sense. The demand is going to be for practical integrators who can step into a real business, understand the workflow, and stitch together the right systems so AI actually drives useful outcomes.</p>

  <p><mark>The companies that win will not just sell software. They will sell adaptation.</mark></p>

  <h2>The Ugly, Boring, High-Value Work</h2>

  <p>This is the part I keep coming back to.</p>

  <p>The biggest opportunities in AI are probably going to belong to people who do two things well at the same time:</p>

  <ol>
    <li>They understand the models.</li>
    <li>They understand the unglamorous realities of how businesses actually work.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>That second part matters more than people think. It is easy to sound smart talking about agents, tooling, orchestration, inference, and evals. It is much harder to sit inside a normal business and understand where revenue actually gets lost.</p>

  <p>That loss usually happens in boring places:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>bad intake</li>
    <li>slow follow-up</li>
    <li>missed calls</li>
    <li>broken handoffs</li>
    <li>admin bottlenecks</li>
    <li>duplicate data entry</li>
    <li>software that nobody really likes using</li>
  </ul>

  <p>That is not glamorous work. But it is incredibly valuable. Because once you connect AI to those points of failure, you are not just adding novelty. You are becoming the nervous system that links intelligence to revenue.</p>

  <p>That is the phrase I keep thinking about here: <strong>the nervous system</strong>. The frontier models are the raw cognition layer. But someone still has to connect that cognition to lead flow, scheduling, quoting, follow-up, routing, dispatch, approvals, reminders, and customer communication. That is where the real operating leverage sits.</p>

  <h2>Why This Matters for Small Business Owners Right Now</h2>

  <p>Most small businesses are not behind because they are lazy. They are behind because they do not have the time, budget, or expertise to rebuild their operations around new technology every six months.</p>

  <p>That is why practical implementation matters more than AI sophistication in a lot of these cases. The business owner does not need a frontier lab. They need a sane workflow. They need someone who can look at the actual operation and say:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>this is where leads are getting lost</li>
    <li>this is where staff time is being burned</li>
    <li>this is where AI can reduce friction</li>
    <li>this is where software should bend to fit your business instead of the other way around</li>
  </ul>

  <p><mark>That is the market I think is about to matter a lot more than people expect.</mark></p>

  <p>Not because the technology is magical, but because most of the economy still runs on businesses that are operationally under-optimized. If you can fix that with AI in a concrete, measurable way, you are sitting in front of an enormous market.</p>

  <h2>Final Thought</h2>

  <p>The people who win this next phase of AI are probably not just going to be the ones closest to the labs. They are going to be the ones who can translate model capability into real business outcomes for ordinary companies.</p>

  <p>That means learning the models, yes. But it also means learning operations, edge cases, ugly workflows, and the practical mechanics of how money actually moves through a business.</p>

  <p>That is less glamorous than building the next frontier model. It is also probably a better business.</p>

